# Lock encoding for the assembly source. The original Borland-era source uses
# code page 437 box-drawing characters (single-byte 0xC4 / 0xC1 / 0xBF / 0xDA
# etc) for the visual divider lines that appear at the top and around every
# proc. Modern editors that re-save as UTF-8 replace each of those with the
# 3-byte U+FFFD replacement sequence (EF BF BD), shredding the visual style.
#
# `working-tree-encoding=ISO-8859-1` keeps the bytes intact in the working
# tree. `eol=crlf text=auto` enforces DOS line endings, since TASM reads
# CRLF-terminated source.
*.ASM   text=auto eol=crlf working-tree-encoding=ISO-8859-1
*.INC   text=auto eol=crlf working-tree-encoding=ISO-8859-1
*.BAT   text=auto eol=crlf

# Markdown / docs / config: normal UTF-8, LF or CRLF either OK.
*.md    text
*.MD    text
